Palestine responds to Israel: We will destroy all agreements to date
Palestinian President Mahmoud Abbas announced at the UN General Assembly on Thursday that he would break all agreements with Israel if the future government of that country tries to fulfill Benjamin Netanyahu's announcement about annexation of the occupied Palestinian territories.
"If the future government of Israel, which will be formed, proceeds to implement this plan, we will nullify all the agreements (with Israel) that have been signed and withdraw from all the commitments that have been made," he declared.
"We will reject the whole plan completely and completely," Abbas threatened under pressure.
“It is our duty to defend all our rights by all possible means, no matter what the consequences, by fully engaging in the application of international law and the fight against terrorism,” declared the President of the Palestinian Authority, who had already made similar statements in July.
Netanyahu, the current prime minister of Israel, was again given the task of forming a government after the September 17 elections.
A week before the election, he announced that if he won, he would annex the Jordan Valley and would annex all Jewish settlements in the West Bank to Israel.
In the early 1990s, Israel and the Palestinians, led by then-President Yasser Arafat, signed a series of peace agreements sponsored by the United States.
Abbas, 84, also promised to hold general elections in Palestinian lands during the UN General Assembly session.
The last one was in 2006.
“After returning to the country, I call for local elections in the West Bank, Gaza and East Jerusalem, and all those who oppose them will have to answer for their actions before God and the international community,” the Palestinian president declared solemnly.
Abbas also defended in his speech the rights of Palestine, treated as a permanent observer in the UN, to exercise the powers of "full members of the UN and all its organs and institutions".
The Palestinian leader concluded by calling on the international community to "force Israel to comply with the United Nations resolutions with full respect".
Israeli Ambassador Danny Danon briefly responded to Abbas's speech, stating that the Palestinian leader "wants to focus the UN on the Palestinian Authority's efforts against Israel rather than fight the calls for terrorism in the Authority under his leadership".
However, Danon did not refer to the annexation of occupied Palestinian lands announced by Netanyahu.
