PLN 105 million for companies from the video game industry from the National Centre for Research and Development
Almost PLN 105 million of the funding will go to companies from the gaming industry, creating innovative solutions.
The National Centre for Research and Development announced on Friday the results of the third edition of the GameINN programme.
Among the nearly 30 projects supported by NCBR, there were: the development of a platform for creating terrain games based on the AR game engine that creates a map of the real world together with an application that allows users to transmit data; a test and training platform for verifying practical skills at work and professional development using VR and AI technologies; an innovative game simulating the management of real production processes using an innovative game model based on the interaction of the virtual world with the real world using the concept of Industry 4.0 – stated in the NCBR communication sent to PAP on Friday.
The aim of the GameINN sectoral programme is to increase the competitiveness of the Polish video game industry on the global market in the perspective of 2023.
As NCBR reports, the Polish video game sector is already growing at a rate of 10% per year.
According to government data, the value of the Polish video game market in 2016 amounted to PLN 1.85 billion, while the forecast for 2019 is PLN 2.23 billion.
"The specially prepared GameINN research agenda and the support for entrepreneurs under this sectoral programme, which already amounts to PLN 300 million, constitute an important impetus for the further, dynamic growth of Polish gamedev", reads the communication.
The video game industry is a perfect example of effective use of the potential we have in Poland.
"The incentives introduced by the government for entrepreneurs who are committed to innovation, such as R&D concessions, competence improvement programs, IP boxes or support programs implemented by NCBR, drive innovative activity of companies and allow them to compete more effectively on a very competitive market," says Jarosław Gowin, Deputy Prime Minister, Minister of Science and Higher Education, quoted in the communication.
The head of the Ministry of Science points out that the money for innovations not only goes to innovators in the form of project funding, but also remains in their pockets – three quarters more entrepreneurs benefited from the R&D rebate in 2018 than a year earlier.
"The amount of deducted costs for R&D activities amounted to PLN 1.7 billion, which gave more than PLN 300 million in savings for companies benefiting from this rebate.
This is the equivalent of the support provided by NCBR in three editions of GameINN”, stresses the Deputy Prime Minister.
NCBR Director Wojciech Kamieniecki, PhD, reminds that in two previous competitions, 78 innovative projects worth a total of over PLN 211.2 million were awarded.
The great interest in the 3rd competition and the variety of applications show that the video game industry has ideas and competences to further develop and increase its competitive advantages.
“I am particularly pleased that among the projects selected – as in previous editions – there are projects concerning solutions not only for entertainment, but also related to Industry 4.0”, he adds.
In the third GameINN competition, entrepreneurs, a consortium of entrepreneurs and a consortium of entrepreneurs with scientific units could apply for funding of up to PLN 20 million.
87 applications for a total amount of PLN 317 million were submitted to NCBR.
The budget of the competition at the time of the announcement was PLN 100 million, but it was increased, so that 27 projects were awarded almost PLN 105 million in co-financing.
Detailed information about the results of GameINN III competition is available on the website ncbr.gov.pl.
The GameINN sector programme is implemented within the Intelligent Development Operational Programme.
NCBR launched the program in 2016 in response to an initiative of entrepreneurs associated in the Polish Games Alliance, which includes companies such as CD Projekt, Techland, CI Games, Bloober Team and 11 bit studios.
