UBS: Gold close to the equilibrium
“The euro will remain around PLN 4.35 in the coming months, which will be accompanied by weak conditions on global markets,” says Michael Bolliger of UBS Wealth Management.
“The expectations of maintaining a solid economic growth rate and a stable monetary policy speak in favour of stabilising the gold prices at the current level,” the specialist in an interview with Bankier.pl estimates.
In his opinion, despite the clear inflationary pressure, the Monetary Policy Council will not decide on rate increases in an environment where the vast majority of central banks are relaxing their policies.
"If the zloty is properly valued – the euro should remain in the range of PLN 4.35 in the coming months – Polish bonds are not attractive enough.
The emerging markets bonds offer significantly higher returns than Polish securities,” says Michael Bolliger, head of asset allocation for emerging markets at UBS Wealth Management.
According to the expert, the main threat to the Polish economy is the deterioration of the global economic situation.
“The global slowdown may deepen, but there should be no severe recession, and at most no fall in GDP growth below zero,” says Michael Bolliger.
"Investors should not underestimate global stocks, which may be damaged by the lack of prospects for resolving the US-China trade conflict and other geopolitical risk factors, including the Trump impeachment procedure and Brexit.
Europe should be the relatively weakest of the stock markets,” according to the latest investor letter from UBS Wealth Management CEO Mark Haefele.
"The actions of the euro area countries should behave worse than the Americans, because they are more vulnerable in the conditions of increased uncertainty around global trade and fears of slowdown", reads the document.
According to Michael Bolliger, after the hossa on the bond markets of the safest countries pushed the profitability of German 10-year bonds even down to minus 0.74 percent, it is still possible to deepen the decline in profitability.
However, in the long term, the profitability of long-term securities should no longer fall, but only of short-term securities, thanks to the easing of banks' monetary policy.
The Fed has the largest scope for rate cuts, which should weaken the US currency in the coming years.
The long-term equilibrium for the euro is the USD 1.29 ceiling, which would mean a 19-percent potential for strengthening the common currency against the dollar.
We expect further Fed rate cuts, which will result in a narrowing of the monetary policy gap in the world.
“The current account and budget deficits may not allow the dollar to maintain its strength in the long term,” says Michael Bolliger.
