GUS: Life in Poland is getting better
The report on household budgets published on Friday by the Central Statistical Office shows that as many as 44 percent of households rated their material situation as good or rather good.
The percentage was 37.2% a year earlier, in 2016 it was 33.5%, and before that – since 2009, when the statistical office first examined subjective assessments of the situation of households – it never exceeded 30%.
In the previous year, a total of 8.1 percent of households considered their material situation to be bad or rather bad, compared to 11.2 percent a year earlier and more than 20 percent in 2009.
The best is the material situation of households of self-employed people.
In this group, it is considered good or rather good by more than 70% of respondents.
On the other extreme are the pensioners' households, where the percentage of such responses was only 18%.
The number of children also has a big influence on the subjective assessment of the material situation of households.
The worst situation is experienced by parents who raise their children alone, of whom 32% declare a good or rather good material situation.
Among couples with children, this percentage varies (depending on the number of children) from 55 to 60 percent, and among households without children it is 48.8 percent.
The effect of the 500+ programme is clearly visible in these statistics.
Before it was launched (in 2016), the worst assessment of their material situation was made by parents raising their children alone and families with many children (with at least three children).
Improving subjective assessments of the material situation of Poles reflects the rapid growth of income, especially from work.
But that is not all, because the percentage of households that consider their situation to be good is increasing faster than real income.
Moreover, at the level of voivodships there is no clear relationship between the level of income and the assessment of the material conditions of households.
The best assessments are made by the inhabitants of the Opole Voivodeship, where 48.9% of the respondents consider their situation as good or rather good.
The following voivodeships are: Lubuskie (47.7%), Śląskie (47.6%), Mazowieckie (47.3%) and zachodniopomorskie (47.1%).
Meanwhile, in Opolskie, the disposable income (i.e. after paying taxes and contributions) amounted to less than 94% of the national average, and in Lubusz, 98%.
The highest incomes were inhabitants of Mazowieckie (120% of the national average) and Silesia (104%).
On average, in Poland, the disposable income per person amounted to PLN 1693 in 2018.
In real terms (after adjustment for the impact of price changes) it increased by 4.3% compared to 2017.
Compared to previous years, this is a fairly low result.
In 2016, per capita income increased by 7%, and a year later by 6.3%.
While the increase in income slows down, it also inhibits the growth in expenditure.
These per person amounted to PLN 1187, which means that in real terms they decreased by 0.7%.
This is the first such case since 2013.
In 2017, expenditure per person increased by 1.9% in real terms, and by 4.3% in 2016.
Research on household budgets suggests that statistical households currently spend 70.1% of their disposable income, while in 2014 this share exceeded 80% and by 2006 it exceeded 90%.
