Gowin: “We must stimulate Polish small trade”
“The effective taxation of hypermarkets does not solve the problem of small trade, we will have to consider whether the state has any instruments to stimulate Polish trade,” said Jarosław Gowin, Deputy Prime Minister, Minister of Science and Higher Education, Leader of the Agreement.
Gowin, during a conversation in the radio station "Sygnałach dnia" (Signs of the Day) in Jedynka, stated that trade is dominated by international networks that impose such low margins on Polish producers that actually Polish companies cannot develop.
Noting that this problem is very difficult to fight, the deputy prime minister reminded that the PiS government tried to face this at the very beginning of the term of office, but got a "counter from the EC".
“We have won before the courts of justice and I hope that if the United Right wins the next elections and forms a government, we will return to this issue,” he said.
He also said that "the effective taxation of hypermarkets does not solve the problem of Polish, and therefore small trade".
“After that, we will have to consider whether the government, the state has any instruments that allow to stimulate Polish trade,” said Gowin.
In May, the EU Court ruled that the European Commission had erred in declaring the Polish retail tax to be an unlawful public aid.
The Retail Sales Tax Act provided for the introduction of two rates of trade tax: 0.8% of income between PLN 17 million and PLN 170 million per month and 1.4% of income above PLN 170 million per month.
The tax was to apply from September 2016.
In September 2016, the EC opened an infringement proceeding against Poland.
Brussels argued at the time that the tax structure could favour smaller shops, which could be considered public aid.
He then claimed that the tax was being imposed in an unlawful manner.
It also ordered the suspension of the tax until it was analysed by officials in Brussels.
Poland did not agree to this position, but the tax collection was suspended.
The EU Court decision in May opened the way for the reintroduction of the tax, but it did not end the matter.
On 24 July, the Commission appealed to the Court of Justice.
On Thursday, the press service of the EUSC informed PAP that the case is currently at a written stage, in which both the European Commission and the Polish government present their arguments in writing.
It is not yet known whether and when the oral procedure, i.e. the hearing of the parties and possible debate, will start.
It takes a good few to a dozen months from the appeal to the announcement of the judgment.
“Such proceedings last on average for a year,” said a source in the Luxembourg Court.
