Voting on the Conservative Party conference recess
The British Parliament voted against a three-day recess in the House of Commons for the Conservative Party's annual conference, which the government requested.
289 voted in favour, 306 against.
The House of Commons does not normally hold any meetings during party conferences, so that Members do not have to resign from either of them or from parliamentary sessions.
However, the opposition parties have recognised that at such a crucial time, the last weeks before the UK's planned exit from the European Union on 31 October, Parliament should not interrupt its work.
The government's request for a recess was approved by 289 MPs, with 306 against.
Two opposition parties after the conventions
The failure to agree to a recess may be seen as political revenge by the opposition on Prime Minister Boris Johnson for his decision to suspend parliament for five weeks (on Tuesday the decision was found by the Supreme Court to be unlawful and unprecedented) and for not wanting to apologize for it after the judges' ruling.
The House of Commons resumed its session on Wednesday, and the most important event of the day was Johnson's speech and the subsequent heated debate.
Johnson accused the opposition of blocking the Brexit and avoiding early elections.
“It is time to implement the Brexit.
It must be implemented in order to respect the result of the referendum.
Brexit must come so that we can deal with an agreement on citizens' priorities, on healthcare, on the cost of living.
Brexit must be realised so that we can unite this country,” Johnson said.
The Conservative Party conference is due to start in Manchester this Sunday and last until Wednesday 2 October.
Conferences of the two main opposition groups – the Labour Party and the Liberal Democrats – have already taken place.
One of the reasons Johnson gave for the long suspension of parliament was party conferences.
