Belgium: Brussels Airlines cancelled 105 flights due to Thomas Cook bankruptcy
Although the British travel agency Thomas Cook has collapsed, his Belgian subsidiary Neckermann is still in operation.
The company has problems.
According to VRT, Brussels Airlines announced that it would cancel 105 flights in October due to problems related to the bankruptcy of Thomas Cook.
Neckermann also laid off 75 employees.
All office trips booked in Belgium will be cancelled, but the holidaymakers will be able to receive a refund.
The court in Ghent also declared the bankruptcy of three Belgian subsidiaries: Thomas Cook Belgium, Thomas Cook Retail and Thomas Cook Financial Services.
Currently, around 12,000 Belgians are abroad on trips bought from Thomas Cook.
Another 40,000 people were to leave the office by the end of the year.
On Monday, Thomas Cook Belgium spokeswoman Leen Segers said the company is now "fully operational" despite the bankruptcy announcement by the British parent company, which caused concern among employees and customers.
The office then reassures that customers who purchased tours there will go on holiday.
Thomas Cook – the oldest and one of the largest travel agencies in the world – announced bankruptcy on the night of Sunday to Monday.
The immediate cause of the bankruptcy was the collapse of last-resort talks with creditors and potential investors on Sunday.
The creditors demanded that, in addition to the £900 million rescue plan agreed in August, the company should secure an additional £200 million for the winter period, when travel agencies usually have lower turnover.
The company's debts have been increasing for several years, resulting in a debt of £1.6 billion.
